article.description: Nykesha Sales scored 10 of her 21 points in the first nine minutes of the second half to help the host Connecticut Sun rally from their biggest deficit of the season and beat the New York Liberty 73-70 Thursday night.
article.headline: Sales' 21 points, five steals energize Sun
article.linkText: Sales leads Sun rally to overcome New York
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- A little anger turned out to be good
thing for the Connecticut Sun.

Down 10 points at the break to the New York Liberty and playing
sloppy ball to get there, the Sun came out fired up and focused the
second half and rallied for a 73-70 win.

"We had some advantages we refused to take advantage of. I just
don't think we played very smart," Sun coach Mike Thibault said.
"The emotional difference was just being mad at how we were
playing."

Nykesha Sales scored 10 of her 21 points in the first nine
minutes of the second half.

Sales also finished with five steals as the Sun (18-5) turned to
defense to overcome a 10-point halftime deficit. Connecticut, which
had not rallied from that far down at the break in a win, remains
perfect at home this season (10-0) and has won 15 straight at
Mohegan Sun Arena dating to last season.

Sales also finished with five steals as the Sun (18-5) turned to
defense to climb back into it. Connecticut, which has the best
record in the league, remains perfect at home this season (10-0)
and has won 15 straight at Mohegan Sun Arena dating to last season.

"Playing 40 minutes is a priority," Sales said. "We have to
try and play like that to prepare for the playoffs because they're
right around the corner."

Ann Wauters had 19 points and 13 rebounds to lead the Liberty
(11-11), who were coming off a last-second loss Wednesday night to
Houston at Madison Square Garden.

Trailing 37-27 at the break, the Sun stunned the Liberty with a
quick second-half turnaround to make up ground in a hurry. Sales
and Katie Douglas combined for all the points in the opening 12-2
run and the Sun pulled even at 39 in the first six minutes.

Connecticut went to a zone defense and forced the Liberty into
two shot-clock violations during that stretch. The second brought a
standing ovation from the crowd of 6,271.

As it turned out, the Sun were just getting warmed up. They
opened an 11-point lead with a 14-3 surge over the next three
minutes. The spurt featured two steals by Sales and consecutive
layups by Lindsay Whalen -- the second after she stole an inbounds
pass.

"We didn't handle their zone defense very well. It doesn't take
a rocket scientist," New York coach Pat Coyle said. "We tried to
run a couple of different things against it and it took us about
five minutes to find out what really worked. When we finally
figured it out, we just didn't keep going back to it."

New York countered down the stretch with four 3-pointers, two
from Elena Baranova. Her second, with 1:56 left, made it 69-65. But
the Liberty stumbled with critical turnovers in the closing
minutes, and the Sun closed it out hitting four of six free throws.

Douglas had 16 points and Taj McWilliams-Franklin added 12. Both
finished with six rebounds.

Becky Hammon finished with 13 points for New York and Baranova
added 11.

Connecticut also got a lift from reserve forward Asjha Jones,
who scored eight of her 10 points in the second half.

"We learned we can win in all different kinds of ways," Jones
said. "We can get big leads or we can stick it out and come from
behind."
